<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-104-862  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 104 862.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  March 14 1989 v3 n11 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Virus prosecution walks unclear line. (legal redress againstperpetrators of computer crime)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brower, Emily.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer VirusesComputer CrimesLegal Issues.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Virus prosecution walks unclear lineandM;Apple and Aldus Corp. of Seattle are still investigating two virus cases andhope to nab the perpetrators under current state and federal computertampering and fraud laws.andM;Apple is investigating the source of the SCORES virus that swept throughWashington, D.C., last spring, according to company representative CynthiaMacon.andM;Dave Lavery of NASA's Office of Aeronautics and Space Technology said the FBIis also investigating the case.andP;  Lavery, who had the dubious distinction ofdiscovering the SCORES virus, said the infection was so widespread thatboundries for jurisdiction are not clear.andM;&quot;We could prosecute under illegal and unauthorized access to federalcomputers, but the question is whether a virus can be considered to act inproxy for a human being,&quot; Lavery said.andM;In Seattle, Aldus has handed the investigation into last spring's infectionof Aldus' FreeHand demonstration disk with the infamous MACMAG virus over tothe King County, Wash., Prosecutors Office.andP;  A Seattle attorney said theoffice could prosecute under tampering and interference laws related tocomputers.andM;Apple and Aldus may eventually succeed in prosecuting, using computertampering laws, but the difficulty of building their cases points to the needfor an amendment like H.R.andP;  55, according to Rep.andP;  Robert Carr, D-Mich.andM;&quot;It's still criminal to write viruses, but the trouble is you need tosynthesize a crime out of other laws,&quot; Carr said.andM;For example, a case could be made against a virus programmer who has stolenor damaged computer data using an ordinary theft statute.andM;&quot;But a normal jury is not likely to think someone misdirecting an electron isa thief,&quot; Carr said.andP;  --andO;</TEXT></DOC>